<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101199161725863></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101199161725863><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=14&mid=101199161725863>Gnome Necromancers</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=14&mid=101199161725863#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=139029><span id= >Yorak</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>2 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Jan 25th 4:48 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well, I personally play a Dark Elf necromancer, and don't have any experience playing as a gnome.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, gnomes seem to be a perfectly viable race for the class.<br><br>Let's do a step-by-step comparison of the gnome necromancer vs. the dark elf necromancer.<br><br>First off, let's start with the attributes.<br><br>Gnomes and Dark Elves both start with 60 str.  No difference there.<br><br>Gnomes start with 70 sta, Dark Elves with 65.  Slight advantage for the gnome; few extra hp to burn.<br><br>Gnomes start with 85 agi, Dark Elves with 90.  Slight advantage for Dark Elves here, although agility is rather unimportant for necromancers.  I belive agility improves AC and helps your dodge skill, which is nice when a monster's on top of you and you want to get a spell off without getting hit, but 5 points is negligable.<br><br>Gnomes start with 95 dex, Dark Elves with 85.  While the gnomes have a slight advantage here, I don't think dexterity does anything for us.  I've heard a rumor that dexterity affects channeling, but I have no idea if it's true or not.<br><br>Gnomes start with 67 wis, Dark Elves with 83.  Numerical advantage for the inkies here, but wisdom is not an attribute we care about.<br><br>Gnomes start with 108 int, Dark Elves with 109.  Very slight advantage for Dark Elves, but one point isn't really going to make a difference.<br><br>Gnomes and Dark Elves both start with 60 cha.  No difference there.<br><br>Now, let's look at their other traits.<br><br>Dark Elves have ultravision, gnomes have infravision.  Ultravision's nice, but infravision still lets you see in the dark.  Slight bonus for Dark Elves there.<br><br>Dark Elves start with the Hide ability, which is at 50 skill.  This is a fairly nice ability at very low levels if you don't have a pet and want to meditate in relative safety.  It's rather unreliable, though.<br><br>The other thing Hide is good for is pet control.  Hiding kills your pet, you see.  This is good when you're in a dungeon and Jebober has wandered off to parts unknown and you're afraid he's going to aggro something and train half the dungeon on you.  Just hide, he dies, and you don't have to worry about it anymore.  Well, not much, anyway...<br><br>Gnomes, on the other hand, get Tinkering.  While I'm not a gnome and have had little experience with tinkered goods (and am personally too impatient for trade skills), I do believe that there are a few handy items that can be tinkered, such as telescopes and rebreathers.<br><br>Finally, there's the faction issue.  While I never cared much for my faction except in a few select places, gnomes, racially, aren't KOS anywhere except Cabilis, whereas Dark Elves are KOS just about everywhere.  The thing is, you're a necromancer, so no one will like you anyway.  However, gnomes might not automatically be KOS, or might have an easier time raising faction with places where they are KOS.  You'd have to ask a gnome about that, though...<br><br>Ultimately, there's not going to be a big difference.  Gnomes make great necros, as far as I can tell.<br>&nbsp;<br>I'm not even here</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
